{
  "Idea": "We propose a meta-learning framework for adaptive teacher scheduling in cycle-teaching systems that leverages real-time representational diagnostics and causal influence estimation to dynamically optimize the sequence of aligners (teachers). In multi-aligner cycle-teaching setups—common in self-improving AI systems, ensemble distillation, or iterative alignment pipelines—the order in which teachers provide feedback significantly impacts final model performance and error accumulation. Current approaches use fixed cycles or performance-based prioritization (e.g., accuracy ranking), which fail to account for representational compatibility, learning trajectory interference, or long-term knowledge coherence.\n\nOur framework introduces a meta-scheduler that observes the evolving latent representations of the student (or recipient aligner) during training and computes two key signals: (1) Representational Diagnostic Metrics (RDMs)—including cosine similarity gradients, Jacobian stability, and cluster cohesion scores across layers—to detect when a teacher's input leads to constructive refinement versus representational collapse or oscillation; and (2) Causal Influence Estimates (CIEs), computed via counterfactual interventions in the teaching graph, measuring how a given teacher’s intervention affects future learning steps (e.g., does Aligner A’s correction make it harder or easier for Aligner B to fix value misalignment?).\n\nThese signals are fed into a lightweight meta-controller—a learned policy network trained via reinforcement learning—which optimizes a reward function balancing immediate improvement, long-term stability, and diversity of teaching sources. The controller learns to skip, repeat, or reorder teachers in the cycle based on real-time diagnostics, effectively creating a personalized teaching itinerary. For instance, if RDMs indicate that the current representation is highly sensitive to adversarial-style corrections, the scheduler may defer a high-variance aligner and instead invoke a stabilizing one. Similarly, if CIE analysis shows that skipping a particular teacher leads to persistent bias downstream, the system proactively reintroduces them even outside their scheduled turn.\n\nThis approach enables the system to avoid destructive interference, minimize error propagation, and promote synergistic alignment. It is particularly impactful in safety-critical domains like medical AI or autonomous systems, where cascading misalignments can have severe consequences. By making the teaching process *introspective* and *causally aware*, our method shifts from passive cycling to active orchestration of knowledge transfer.\n\nPotential applications include iterative DPO (Direct Preference Optimization) pipelines, recursive reward modeling, and multi-expert distillation in large language models. The framework is modular and can integrate with existing aligners without requiring architectural changes on their part.",
